The findings and conclusions in this report are those of the authors and do not necessarily represent the official position of any organization or government. The ASER Centre makes no representations or warranties of any kind, express or implied, about the completeness, accuracy, reliability, suitability or availability with respect to the information contained in this report.

### I. About ASER

ASER is a citizen-led initiative that has been measuring learning outcomes in rural India since 2005. The survey is conducted annually and covers all children aged 3-16 years in sampled villages. The survey is designed to be representative of the rural population. The findings of the survey are used to inform policy and advocacy efforts to improve education in India.

### J. Partners

ASER is supported by a wide network of partners, including:

*   Pratham
*   UNICEF
*   World Bank
*   Government of India
*   State Governments
*   Civil Society Organizations
*   Volunteers

### K. Volunteers

ASER relies on the support of thousands of volunteers who conduct the survey every year. We thank all the volunteers for their hard work and dedication.

### L. Data Availability

The ASER data is available for public use. Researchers and policymakers can access the data through the ASER Centre website.

### M. Future Directions

ASER is continuously working to improve the survey methodology and expand the scope of the survey. Future surveys will include more detailed information on learning outcomes, teacher quality, and school infrastructure. ASER will also explore new ways to engage with communities and policymakers to improve education in India.

### N. Conclusion

ASER provides valuable insights into the state of education in rural India. The survey highlights the progress that has been made in enrollment and infrastructure, but also the challenges that remain in improving learning outcomes. ASER calls on all stakeholders to work together to ensure that every child in India receives a quality education.

### O. Endnotes

1.  The ASER sample is designed to be representative of the rural population. The sample is selected using a two-stage stratified random sampling procedure.
2.  The learning assessments are brief and may not capture the full range of children's skills.
3.  The data is cross-sectional and does not capture changes over time for individual children.
4.  The sample size may be small for some states or districts.
5.  The survey is limited to rural areas.

